3.6.1 Libraries

Load R packages:

library(MASS)
library(ISLR)

3.6.2 Simple Linear Regression

Print column names:

names(Boston)
##  [1] "crim"    "zn"      "indus"   "chas"    "nox"     "rm"      "age"    
##  [8] "dis"     "rad"     "tax"     "ptratio" "black"   "lstat"   "medv"

Regress medv on lstat (median home value on percent of households with low socioeconomic status):

lm.fit = lm(medv~lstat, data=Boston)

Print a summary of the model:

summary(lm.fit)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = medv ~ lstat, data = Boston)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -15.168  -3.990  -1.318   2.034  24.500 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 34.55384    0.56263   61.41   <2e-16 ***
## lstat       -0.95005    0.03873  -24.53   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 6.216 on 504 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.5441, Adjusted R-squared:  0.5432 
## F-statistic: 601.6 on 1 and 504 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Get coefficients of the model:

coef(lm.fit)
## (Intercept)       lstat 
##  34.5538409  -0.9500494

Get confidence interval of the model coefficients:

confint(lm.fit)
##                 2.5 %     97.5 %
## (Intercept) 33.448457 35.6592247
## lstat       -1.026148 -0.8739505

Predict values for medv given values of lstat, returning a confidence interval:

predict(lm.fit, data.frame(lstat=c(5, 10, 15)), interval="confidence")
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 29.80359 29.00741 30.59978
## 2 25.05335 24.47413 25.63256
## 3 20.30310 19.73159 20.87461

Now returning a prediction interval:

predict(lm.fit, data.frame(lstat=c(5, 10, 15)), interval="prediction")
##        fit       lwr      upr
## 1 29.80359 17.565675 42.04151
## 2 25.05335 12.827626 37.27907
## 3 20.30310  8.077742 32.52846

Plot the least squares regression line:

plot(Boston$lstat, Boston$medv)
abline(lm.fit, lwd=3, col="red")

Experiment with plotting options:

plot(1:20, 1:20, pch=1:20)

Generate default diagnostic plots for the model:

par(mfrow=c(2, 2))
plot(lm.fit)

Plot the residuals:

plot(predict(lm.fit), residuals(lm.fit))

Plot the studentized residuals:

plot(predict(lm.fit), rstudent(lm.fit))

Looks like there’s some nonlinearity!

Compute leverage statistics:

plot(hatvalues(lm.fit))

Find the index of the observation with the largest leverage statistic:

which.max(hatvalues(lm.fit))
## 375 
## 375

And the observation itself:

Boston[which.max(hatvalues(lm.fit)), 'lstat']
## [1] 37.97

3.6.3 Multiple Linear Regression

To fit a model with n predictors, use the following syntax:

lm.fit = lm(y~x1+x2+...+x3)

Fit a model to medv using lstat and age:

lm.fit = lm(medv~lstat+age, data=Boston)
summary(lm.fit)

3.6.4 Interaction Terms

Use the syntax x1:x2 to add an interaction term between x1 and x2, or use x1*x2 to include both predictors and the interaction term at the same time (a shorthand for x1+x2+x1:x2):

summary(lm(medv~lstat*age, data=Boston))
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = medv ~ lstat * age, data = Boston)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -15.806  -4.045  -1.333   2.085  27.552 
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 36.0885359  1.4698355  24.553  < 2e-16 ***
## lstat       -1.3921168  0.1674555  -8.313 8.78e-16 ***

## lstat:age    0.0041560  0.0018518   2.244   0.0252 *

## 
## Residual standard error: 6.149 on 502 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.5557, Adjusted R-squared:  0.5531 
## F-statistic: 209.3 on 3 and 502 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

3.6.5 Non-linear Transformations of the Predictors

To create nonlinear transformations of predictors in the context of a linear model formula, use the built-in I() function to ensure that ^ is treated “as-is” (and not using the formula-specific syntax):

lm.fit2 = lm(medv~lstat+I(lstat^2), data=Boston)
summary(lm.fit2)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = medv ~ lstat + I(lstat^2), data = Boston)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -15.2834  -3.8313  -0.5295   2.3095  25.4148 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 42.862007   0.872084   49.15   <2e-16 ***
## lstat       -2.332821   0.123803  -18.84   <2e-16 ***
## I(lstat^2)   0.043547   0.003745   11.63   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.524 on 503 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.6407, Adjusted R-squared:  0.6393 
## F-statistic: 448.5 on 2 and 503 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

We can use the anova function to test the hypothesis that the model with a nonlinear term is superior to the original model (the null hypothesis is that both models perform equally well):

lm.fit = lm(medv~lstat, data=Boston)
anova(lm.fit, lm.fit2)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Model 1: medv ~ lstat
## Model 2: medv ~ lstat + I(lstat^2)
##   Res.Df   RSS Df Sum of Sq     F    Pr(>F)    
## 1    504 19472                                 
## 2    503 15347  1    4125.1 135.2 < 2.2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Plot the diagnostics for the new model to confirm that the residual plot has improved:

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(lm.fit2)

For higher-order polynomials, use the built-in poly() function:

lm.fit5 = lm(medv~poly(lstat, 5), data=Boston)

3.6.6 Qualitative Predictors

Examine the predictors in the Carseats dataset:

names(Carseats)
##  [1] "Sales"       "CompPrice"   "Income"      "Advertising" "Population" 
##  [6] "Price"       "ShelveLoc"   "Age"         "Education"   "Urban"      
## [11] "US"

In this case, ShelveLoc is a qualitative predictor, which can take the value of Bad, Medium, or Good (corresponding to the placement of the car seat on the store shelf). Given such a qualitative variable, R generates dummy variables automatically.

Fit a multiple regression model with some interaction terms:

lm.fit = lm(Sales~.+Income:Advertising+Price:Age, data=Carseats)
summary(lm.fit)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Sales ~ . + Income:Advertising + Price:Age, data = Carseats)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -2.9208 -0.7503  0.0177  0.6754  3.3413 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                      Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)         6.5755654  1.0087470   6.519 2.22e-10 ***
## CompPrice           0.0929371  0.0041183  22.567  < 2e-16 ***
## Income              0.0108940  0.0026044   4.183 3.57e-05 ***
## Advertising         0.0702462  0.0226091   3.107 0.002030 ** 
## Population          0.0001592  0.0003679   0.433 0.665330    
## Price              -0.1008064  0.0074399 -13.549  < 2e-16 ***
## ShelveLocGood       4.8486762  0.1528378  31.724  < 2e-16 ***
## ShelveLocMedium     1.9532620  0.1257682  15.531  < 2e-16 ***
## Age                -0.0579466  0.0159506  -3.633 0.000318 ***
## Education          -0.0208525  0.0196131  -1.063 0.288361    
## UrbanYes            0.1401597  0.1124019   1.247 0.213171    
## USYes              -0.1575571  0.1489234  -1.058 0.290729    
## Income:Advertising  0.0007510  0.0002784   2.698 0.007290 ** 
## Price:Age           0.0001068  0.0001333   0.801 0.423812    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.011 on 386 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.8761, Adjusted R-squared:  0.8719 
## F-statistic:   210 on 13 and 386 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Use the constrasts() function to read out the coding that R uses for the dummy variables under the hood:

contrasts(Carseats$ShelveLoc)
##        Good Medium
## Bad       0      0
## Good      1      0
## Medium    0      1

Since the coefficients for ShelveLocGood and ShelveLocMedium are both positive and significant in the summary above, we can say with confidence that Good and Medium shelf positions both predict higher sales than Bad shelf positions. Further, since the coefficient for ShelveLocGood is greater than the coefficient for ShelveLocMedium, we can be confident that a Good shelf position will be better for sales than a Medium shelf position.

3.6.7 Writing Functions

Write a simple function to load the MASS and ISLR libraries:

LoadLibraries = function() {
    library(ISLR)
    library(MASS)
    print("The MASS and ISLR libraries have been loaded.")
}

Call the function:

LoadLibraries()
## [1] "The MASS and ISLR libraries have been loaded."
